  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Education and Livelihoods for Girls and Women (Ethiopia)</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Many girls and disabled children in Ethiopia never go to school, especially in poor families and rural areas. Girls that start school often drop out because families need them to work, or because of early marriage, and the provision of education for disabled children is scarce. Disability and Development Partners train teachers to enable them to work with disabled children, and support schools to make them more accessible. Loans to families generate sufficient income so that children are not forced to work. The project engages parents and community leaders to discuss the importance of education to children. Part of these community discussions focus on early marriage and the practice of genital mutilation. As a result, thousands of girls and disabled children who have never been to school, or who would have dropped out, receive a basic education. The project also aims to reduce the incidence of early marriage and genital mutilation. In addition to the project grant, Disability and Development Partners have been awarded &#xA3;27,200 to help strengthen the organisation and their work, enabling them to support their local partners in Africa to continue to provide effective solutions to the issues they address.</narrative>
  </description>
